        "title": "The \"Full Coverage\" Trap Is Making You Look Older",
        "body_text": "<p>It seems logical. You want to cover age spots, redness, and uneven tone — so you reach for the heaviest coverage you can find. Full coverage. Maximum pigment. Total concealment. And in doing so, you've fallen into the single biggest mistake women over 50 make with foundation.</p><p>Full coverage formulas are loaded with dense pigments and binding agents that create an opaque, mask-like layer. On younger skin with minimal texture, this can look passable. On mature skin — where there are fine lines, pores, and natural changes in surface texture — it amplifies every single detail you were trying to hide. It's like putting a magnifying glass on your face.</p><p>The women who get compliments on their skin have learned a counterintuitive truth: less coverage, applied correctly, looks far more flawless than heavy coverage ever could. A sheer, buildable formula lets your natural skin show through in the places where it looks good, while allowing you to layer more coverage only where you actually need it.</p>",
        "link_text": "",
